Over last 40 years, there are no cases in which a week 21 value of ≥ 83% did not result in a week 22 value of ≥90%. Given that we're working with 88% in today's report, and there is some decent weather in subject region to round out the subject timeframe, I feel confident at 100%.

Today's planting report is out [1] and is at 88%, falling slightly behind the industry estimate of 90% [2]. The question now is, will the last 2% be planted in the next week. The states heavily lagging include NY, PA and ND. ND looks quite clear weather-wise, though NY & PA look like they have 2-3 days of rain coming in the next week (Google weather search for major cities in up-state NY and PA; Fargo for ND).

As of 17 May 2020, 18 states have completed 92% of the planting with only the hardest acres available in the remaining states. Particularly, in the Dakotas, there are still standing crops. Hence, it is highly likely that the planting will reach a target of more than 90%.

Reviewing the latest progress, planing is well ahead of the 5-year average [1], at 67% planted [2], with most states running well ahead of their usual plantings. Bumping more up to over 90.

As on 12 May 2020, as per USDA survey, already 67% of the estimated crop is planted. With the same pattern of the impact of corona, the corn planting trend may not be affected in the next 3 weeks. With all other conditions such as steady availability of inputs, futures price of corn ( it appears to be bearish) and shorter time to make an alternate decision to switch crops, it is highly likely that the USDA estimates will be reached by 31 May. The USDA data also shows most of the 19 states have shown higher planted area than that in 2019 for the same time last year. The weather forecast is also favorable so that plantings are not delayed.
67%. Still ahead of schedule but this is a slower rise than expected.

67% reported today, just a smidge below the last-40-years median of 69%. Given we were pretty far ahead last week, it was lower than I expected this week, so I'm hedging a tiny bit, given that there have been 2 years [1] higher than 67% at this point that fell just short of 90% (1990 and 1982, 69%-88% and 69%-89% respectively). That said, there have been 14 of 40 years that were lower than 67% at this point that still managed to get to 96% by the last week, so far more evidence that we're on track/can catch up if needed than otherwise.

Based on the latest data from the USDA [1], this year's crop is running well ahead of the 5-year trend. Updating forecast to shift more weight to 90% percent. There are reports that all the corn in Iowa will be in the ground by next week, due to good soil conditions [2]. Ohio is running behind the 5 year average, though ahead of last year [3]. MN is running well ahead of last year due to good weather and 2 weeks ahead of the 5 year average [4]. With the high-level numbers running well-ahead, and good local results from a few samples, changing my forecast to be more heavily on 90%.

REVISION TO EARLIER ESTIMATES after I realized that the report on which the question will be resolved this year will be the 9th of the season, not the 8th, per the USDA release calendar. A week can make a big difference on this one, it seems.

“The USDA's most recent weekly Crop Progress report indicated that only 23 percent of the corn acreage in 18 major producing states was planted as of May 5, compared to a five-year average of 46 percent.May 9, 2019”

Probabilities derived from 1,000 simulations of a Weibull distribution with shape (13.5) and scale (92.4) estimated from reported values for week 8 (approx. end of May/start of June) of the reporting period from the years 1995 to 2019. (N.B. Did not bootstrap to address uncertainty in those estimates.) Chose Weibull after exploring a few options via the 'fitdistrplus' package in R.
